[7] Philippines (Caraga)
Date: Tue 25 Jun 2019 4:38 PM PHT
Source: Manila Bulletin [edited]
https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/06/25/doh-caraga-continues-battles-vs-measles-as-death-toll-rises-to-20/


Health workers from the Department of Health Center for Health Development (DOH CHD) Caraga, together with their local government unit (LGU) counterparts, continued to battle measles disease as the death toll from the infectious disease rose to 20.

In the latest update from the Center for Health Development (CHD) [in Butuan City on [Tue 25 Jun 2019], a total of 1206 cases of measles have been reported from different disease reporting units in the region from [1 Jan-22 Jun 2019].

"This is 506% higher compared to the reported cases last year [2018]," the regional office of the DOH 13 said. With this number of cases, the CHD Caraga has mobilized nurses hired under contract of service to augment the local health staff in advocacy and vaccination activities.

Logistics and vaccines are pre-positioned at the Provincial Health Offices (PHOs) for easy access by respective Rural Health Units (RHUs).

Rapid Coverage Assessment (RCA) was done by the DOH CHD Caraga staff regionwide to ensure that all barangays are covered by vaccination teams.

Heightened advocacy utilizing major communication channels were also used to strengthen advocacy for immunization.

However, with all these efforts, new clustering cases have been detected since 26 May until 22 Jun.

The majority of the new reported cases came from Agusan del Sur, specifically in far-flung towns of La Paz, Loreto, Rosario, San Luis, and Talacogon.

Since the start of the year [2019], a cumulative report of 20 deaths, classified as suspected measles deaths had been recorded by CHD Caraga. Of the 20 reported suspected measles cases, 18 came from the Agusan del Sur. The latest of these reported deaths were in the month of June coming from San Luis (2), Loreto (3), and Talacogon (4) towns.

In its initial investigation, the CHD Caraga has noted that cases come from indigenous peoples communities.

Members of these communities are often mobile, meaning their settlements are often transferred from one area to another.

Following initial reports, the DOH 13 Caraga has sent 2 Rapid Response Teams (RRTs) together with the staff from the Provincial Health Office of Agusan del Sur to Talacogon on 11-13 Jun and to Loreto on 20-22 Jun 2019.

[Byline: Mike Crismundo]

